WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:28.321 align:middle line:90%


00:00:28.321 --> 00:00:30.820 align:middle line:10%
>>REGINA MEREDITH: One of the
fastest disappearing practices

00:00:30.820 --> 00:00:34.880 align:middle line:10%
in Western culture is sleep,
so sweet yet so far away

00:00:34.880 --> 00:00:36.490 align:middle line:10%
for so many people.

00:00:36.490 --> 00:00:38.320 align:middle line:84%
But what is this
doing to our lives?

00:00:38.320 --> 00:00:40.710 align:middle line:84%
What actually happens
when we sleep?

00:00:40.710 --> 00:00:43.830 align:middle line:84%
From crossing between worlds
to restoring our immune systems

00:00:43.830 --> 00:00:45.500 align:middle line:84%
and neural networks,
sleep is one

00:00:45.500 --> 00:00:48.250 align:middle line:84%
of the most important
practices of being human.

00:00:48.250 --> 00:00:51.820 align:middle line:84%
Kat Duff loves to sleep and
began a years-long project

00:00:51.820 --> 00:00:54.040 align:middle line:84%
to document what
happens when we sleep,

00:00:54.040 --> 00:00:56.800 align:middle line:84%
which became the basis of
her book "The Secret Life

00:00:56.800 --> 00:00:57.570 align:middle line:90%
of Sleep."

00:00:57.570 --> 00:00:59.380 align:middle line:90%
And Kat's here with us today.

00:00:59.380 --> 00:01:00.460 align:middle line:90%
You love to sleep?

00:01:00.460 --> 00:01:01.720 align:middle line:90%
>>KAT DUFF: I do, Regina.

00:01:01.720 --> 00:01:03.790 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Tell me when
you became just fascinated

00:01:03.790 --> 00:01:05.367 align:middle line:90%
with the subject of sleep.

00:01:05.367 --> 00:01:07.950 align:middle line:84%
>>DUFF: You know, I'd loved to
sleep when I was a little girl.

00:01:07.950 --> 00:01:09.950 align:middle line:90%
It was my favorite time of day.

00:01:09.950 --> 00:01:12.850 align:middle line:10%
I loved going in my
room, shutting the door,

00:01:12.850 --> 00:01:15.880 align:middle line:10%
turning off the
light, and it felt

00:01:15.880 --> 00:01:20.040 align:middle line:10%
like it was a huge world that
I got to go to in my sleep.

00:01:20.040 --> 00:01:21.650 align:middle line:10%
And then in the
morning, waking up.

00:01:21.650 --> 00:01:23.530 align:middle line:10%
OK, I've got to do this life.

00:01:23.530 --> 00:01:25.184 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yeah.

00:01:25.184 --> 00:01:26.600 align:middle line:84%
>>DUFF: And I
always wondered, how

00:01:26.600 --> 00:01:27.870 align:middle line:90%
is it that sleep changes me?

00:01:27.870 --> 00:01:30.710 align:middle line:84%
Because I would notice
that I'd feel changed.

00:01:30.710 --> 00:01:33.640 align:middle line:84%
I'd wake up in a
better mood usually.

00:01:33.640 --> 00:01:37.680 align:middle line:84%
I'd wake up remembering
things for the tests better

00:01:37.680 --> 00:01:41.010 align:middle line:84%
than when I has
studied the day before.

00:01:41.010 --> 00:01:43.840 align:middle line:84%
Sometimes I would wake up
with a different feeling

00:01:43.840 --> 00:01:46.047 align:middle line:84%
about a situation than
I'd had the night before.

00:01:46.047 --> 00:01:48.130 align:middle line:84%
Something that had been
really upsetting the night

00:01:48.130 --> 00:01:50.612 align:middle line:84%
before suddenly
wasn't so upsetting.

00:01:50.612 --> 00:01:52.320 align:middle line:84%
It seemed like, oh,
I can deal with that.

00:01:52.320 --> 00:01:52.910 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Mm hmm.

00:01:52.910 --> 00:01:54.368 align:middle line:84%
And you're lucky,
because there are

00:01:54.368 --> 00:01:57.289 align:middle line:84%
people who go to sleep at night
and dread the experience--

00:01:57.289 --> 00:01:58.080 align:middle line:90%
>>DUFF: Absolutely.

00:01:58.080 --> 00:02:00.990 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: --who have night
terrors and horrid dreams

00:02:00.990 --> 00:02:01.900 align:middle line:90%
and so forth.

00:02:01.900 --> 00:02:01.940 align:middle line:90%
>>DUFF: Yeah.

00:02:01.940 --> 00:02:03.314 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: And
we're going to talk

00:02:03.314 --> 00:02:05.630 align:middle line:84%
about all the guises of
sleep and what it looks like

00:02:05.630 --> 00:02:07.780 align:middle line:84%
and how different
people experience it.

00:02:07.780 --> 00:02:09.940 align:middle line:84%
And one of things I wanted
to start off with here,

00:02:09.940 --> 00:02:14.290 align:middle line:84%
because it's really
a shame that it's

00:02:14.290 --> 00:02:17.970 align:middle line:84%
such a common
phrase among people

00:02:17.970 --> 00:02:21.600 align:middle line:84%
in the Western world, which
is you snooze, you lose.

00:02:21.600 --> 00:02:25.425 align:middle line:84%
And so this is bringing about
a mindset for many people

00:02:25.425 --> 00:02:27.300 align:middle line:84%
that, oh, god, I wish
I didn't have to sleep.

00:02:27.300 --> 00:02:28.565 align:middle line:90%
Sleep is such a waste of time.

00:02:28.565 --> 00:02:30.440 align:middle line:84%
I wish I could get by
on three or four hours.

00:02:30.440 --> 00:02:33.023 align:middle line:84%
Well, a lot of people actually
are getting by on three or four

00:02:33.023 --> 00:02:34.350 align:middle line:90%
hours because they can't sleep.

00:02:34.350 --> 00:02:36.930 align:middle line:84%
But what is that doing
to us as a culture,

00:02:36.930 --> 00:02:39.575 align:middle line:90%
this you snooze, you lose?

00:02:39.575 --> 00:02:41.200 align:middle line:84%
>>DUFF: You snooze,
you lose, I take it

00:02:41.200 --> 00:02:43.640 align:middle line:84%
back to Ben Franklin,
who used to say

00:02:43.640 --> 00:02:46.150 align:middle line:84%
that we sleep
enough in the grave.

00:02:46.150 --> 00:02:49.050 align:middle line:84%
That Western and
especially American

00:02:49.050 --> 00:02:53.080 align:middle line:84%
tradition of that
Protestant work ethic

00:02:53.080 --> 00:02:55.060 align:middle line:84%
that says sleep is
a waste of time,

00:02:55.060 --> 00:02:57.710 align:middle line:84%
we've got better
things to do, one

00:02:57.710 --> 00:03:00.050 align:middle line:84%
of the most difficult things
about that, of course,

00:03:00.050 --> 00:03:02.014 align:middle line:84%
is that we don't
function as well when

00:03:02.014 --> 00:03:03.305 align:middle line:90%
we aren't getting enough sleep.

00:03:03.305 --> 00:03:05.780 align:middle line:84%
We're more likely to
focus on the negative.

00:03:05.780 --> 00:03:09.380 align:middle line:84%
We're more likely to create
conflicts, to be aggressive,

00:03:09.380 --> 00:03:12.420 align:middle line:84%
to be unwilling to
resolve conflicts.

00:03:12.420 --> 00:03:15.250 align:middle line:84%
We have a harder time
remembering things.

00:03:15.250 --> 00:03:17.310 align:middle line:90%
We have poor judgment.

00:03:17.310 --> 00:03:19.730 align:middle line:90%
We take risks we shouldn't take.

00:03:19.730 --> 00:03:22.530 align:middle line:84%
That kind of sums up our
culture in some ways.

00:03:22.530 --> 00:03:24.370 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: It does
in a lot of ways.

00:03:24.370 --> 00:03:28.370 align:middle line:84%
It creates also a
lack of patience

00:03:28.370 --> 00:03:31.070 align:middle line:84%
and sometimes irresponsible
behaviors and such.

00:03:31.070 --> 00:03:31.939 align:middle line:90%
Poor judgment.

00:03:31.939 --> 00:03:32.480 align:middle line:90%
>>DUFF: Yeah.

00:03:32.480 --> 00:03:33.040 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Poor judgement.

00:03:33.040 --> 00:03:35.550 align:middle line:84%
>>DUFF: There are some people,
a very small percentage

00:03:35.550 --> 00:03:38.290 align:middle line:84%
of the population, that is
actually genetically inclined

00:03:38.290 --> 00:03:40.480 align:middle line:84%
to get by on three or
four hours of sleep.

00:03:40.480 --> 00:03:42.350 align:middle line:84%
But a lot more
people try to do it

00:03:42.350 --> 00:03:43.840 align:middle line:84%
than can actually
get away with it.

00:03:43.840 --> 00:03:44.300 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Right.

00:03:44.300 --> 00:03:45.758 align:middle line:84%
>>DUFF: And one of
the first things

00:03:45.758 --> 00:03:47.210 align:middle line:84%
we lose when we're
sleep deprived

00:03:47.210 --> 00:03:49.970 align:middle line:84%
is our ability to reflect
on our own behavior.

00:03:49.970 --> 00:03:52.780 align:middle line:84%
So when someone tells me I
do just fine on three or four

00:03:52.780 --> 00:03:55.292 align:middle line:84%
hours, I like to go to their
family members and ask them--

00:03:55.292 --> 00:03:56.750 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Yeah,
how are they doing?

00:03:56.750 --> 00:03:58.630 align:middle line:90%
>>DUFF: --how patient are they?

00:03:58.630 --> 00:04:00.470 align:middle line:90%
Or to their coworkers.

00:04:00.470 --> 00:04:01.900 align:middle line:90%
Are they making many mistakes?

00:04:01.900 --> 00:04:02.840 align:middle line:90%
That kind of thing.

00:04:02.840 --> 00:04:06.504 align:middle line:84%
Because we don't realize when
we are not functioning as well.

00:04:06.504 --> 00:04:07.170 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Right.

00:04:07.170 --> 00:04:08.090 align:middle line:90%
That becomes our reality.

00:04:08.090 --> 00:04:08.640 align:middle line:90%
>>DUFF: Yeah.

00:04:08.640 --> 00:04:11.130 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: So I noticed when
I was in India, for example,

00:04:11.130 --> 00:04:14.960 align:middle line:84%
such a completely
different idea about sleep.

00:04:14.960 --> 00:04:17.410 align:middle line:84%
At first, it was
kind of shocking,

00:04:17.410 --> 00:04:20.240 align:middle line:84%
in that I saw people
sleeping kind of everywhere,

00:04:20.240 --> 00:04:21.399 align:middle line:90%
on the side of the road.

00:04:21.399 --> 00:04:21.940 align:middle line:90%
>>DUFF: Yeah.

00:04:21.940 --> 00:04:23.760 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: I remember
walking into a cafe,

00:04:23.760 --> 00:04:27.420 align:middle line:84%
and I walked around the uncle
who was sleeping on the floor

00:04:27.420 --> 00:04:31.140 align:middle line:84%
next to a plate of tomatoes
that had been cooked

00:04:31.140 --> 00:04:33.660 align:middle line:84%
and were settling down, the
juices were settling down,

00:04:33.660 --> 00:04:34.160 align:middle line:90%
a big plate.

00:04:34.160 --> 00:04:36.720 align:middle line:84%
And he was just passed out
next to them on the floor,

00:04:36.720 --> 00:04:38.220 align:middle line:84%
and you just walked
around the uncle

00:04:38.220 --> 00:04:39.690 align:middle line:90%
and went on about your business.

00:04:39.690 --> 00:04:44.050 align:middle line:84%
And sleep is really not
anything to be ashamed of

00:04:44.050 --> 00:04:47.229 align:middle line:84%
but should be done whenever
you're inspired to do so.

00:04:47.229 --> 00:04:47.770 align:middle line:90%
>>DUFF: Yeah.

00:04:47.770 --> 00:04:48.500 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:04:48.500 --> 00:04:49.000 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:04:49.000 --> 00:04:51.980 align:middle line:84%
I was really interested in
the historical perspectives

00:04:51.980 --> 00:04:54.360 align:middle line:84%
on sleep and
cross-cultural ones.

00:04:54.360 --> 00:04:58.760 align:middle line:84%
We have really, in our
westernized cultures,

00:04:58.760 --> 00:05:01.600 align:middle line:84%
really privatized sleep
in the modern age.

00:05:01.600 --> 00:05:04.290 align:middle line:84%
Now before the Industrial
Age, before the advent

00:05:04.290 --> 00:05:08.760 align:middle line:84%
of artificial light, people
slept more communally.

00:05:08.760 --> 00:05:14.220 align:middle line:84%
They often slept twice
a day or twice a night.

00:05:14.220 --> 00:05:15.880 align:middle line:84%
But now we have
this habit where we

00:05:15.880 --> 00:05:18.540 align:middle line:84%
think that we have to
go off by ourselves

00:05:18.540 --> 00:05:21.102 align:middle line:84%
and have very special
conditions to sleep in.

00:05:21.102 --> 00:05:22.810 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: And do it
in one concentrated--

00:05:22.810 --> 00:05:23.430 align:middle line:90%
>>DUFF: In one spell.

00:05:23.430 --> 00:05:24.030 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yeah.

00:05:24.030 --> 00:05:24.613 align:middle line:90%
>>DUFF: Right.

00:05:24.613 --> 00:05:25.410 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Mm hmm.

00:05:25.410 --> 00:05:25.970 align:middle line:90%
No.

00:05:25.970 --> 00:05:26.260 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:05:26.260 --> 00:05:28.000 align:middle line:84%
So now a little bit
about your background.

00:05:28.000 --> 00:05:30.541 align:middle line:84%
You were involved for many years
in the study of neuroscience

00:05:30.541 --> 00:05:31.530 align:middle line:90%
and neurofeedback.

00:05:31.530 --> 00:05:32.260 align:middle line:90%
>>DUFF: Mm hmm.

00:05:32.260 --> 00:05:33.718 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: And I'm
going to bring up

00:05:33.718 --> 00:05:36.030 align:middle line:90%
the subject of Eugene Asbrinsky.

00:05:36.030 --> 00:05:37.030 align:middle line:90%
I think that's how you--

00:05:37.030 --> 00:05:37.110 align:middle line:90%
>>DUFF: Oh, yes.

00:05:37.110 --> 00:05:37.750 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yes.

00:05:37.750 --> 00:05:41.290 align:middle line:84%
And let's talk about how your
background in neurofeedback

00:05:41.290 --> 00:05:44.380 align:middle line:84%
fed into the research and
understanding of sleep.

00:05:44.380 --> 00:05:48.418 align:middle line:84%
>>DUFF: I'd actually started
studying neurosciences

00:05:48.418 --> 00:05:50.626 align:middle line:84%
long before that, before
the neurofeedback, actually,

00:05:50.626 --> 00:05:53.810 align:middle line:84%
with the-- I worked with
a lot of trauma survivors.

00:05:53.810 --> 00:05:56.490 align:middle line:84%
And of course there's a
very neurological component

00:05:56.490 --> 00:05:58.010 align:middle line:90%
to post-traumatic stress.

00:05:58.010 --> 00:05:59.830 align:middle line:90%
So I started studying that then.

00:05:59.830 --> 00:06:01.690 align:middle line:84%
And also, as a
counselor we learn a lot

00:06:01.690 --> 00:06:04.710 align:middle line:84%
about neurological
development in infancy

00:06:04.710 --> 00:06:07.530 align:middle line:84%
and the conditions
of infancy that

00:06:07.530 --> 00:06:10.000 align:middle line:90%
create later states of mind.

00:06:10.000 --> 00:06:12.010 align:middle line:84%
But then about 10 years
ago I got interested

00:06:12.010 --> 00:06:18.540 align:middle line:84%
in neurofeedback, so I continued
that study of neurosciences.

00:06:18.540 --> 00:06:24.440 align:middle line:84%
And the relationship between
what's going on neurologically

00:06:24.440 --> 00:06:28.300 align:middle line:84%
and how we think and how we feel
is really a fascinating one.

00:06:28.300 --> 00:06:31.840 align:middle line:84%
And one of the things I learned
as a neurofeedback therapist

00:06:31.840 --> 00:06:35.810 align:middle line:84%
especially is that no matter
what problem someone walks

00:06:35.810 --> 00:06:39.290 align:middle line:84%
in the door with, if we
can help them sleep better,

00:06:39.290 --> 00:06:41.190 align:middle line:84%
usually that problem
gets better--

00:06:41.190 --> 00:06:41.480 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Interesting.

00:06:41.480 --> 00:06:41.979 align:middle line:90%
So simple.

00:06:41.979 --> 00:06:44.590 align:middle line:84%
>>DUFF: --whether it's
depression, anxiety,

00:06:44.590 --> 00:06:46.860 align:middle line:90%
impulse control, all of those.

00:06:46.860 --> 00:06:50.230 align:middle line:84%
So I very quickly learned
to put into my intake,

00:06:50.230 --> 00:06:50.989 align:middle line:90%
how do you sleep?

00:06:50.989 --> 00:06:52.030 align:middle line:90%
Tell me about your sleep.

00:06:52.030 --> 00:06:53.470 align:middle line:90%
How long do you sleep?

00:06:53.470 --> 00:06:55.100 align:middle line:90%
How do you fall asleep?

00:06:55.100 --> 00:06:57.390 align:middle line:84%
Those kinds of things are
very important to consider

00:06:57.390 --> 00:06:59.580 align:middle line:84%
in terms of our mental
and emotional well-being.

00:06:59.580 --> 00:07:02.270 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: And then we
all know as time went on,

00:07:02.270 --> 00:07:05.902 align:middle line:90%
starting in 1953 with Asbrinsky?

00:07:05.902 --> 00:07:06.860 align:middle line:90%
>>DUFF: Aserinsky, yes.

00:07:06.860 --> 00:07:07.080 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Aserinsky?

00:07:07.080 --> 00:07:07.830 align:middle line:90%
>>DUFF: Mm hmm.

00:07:07.830 --> 00:07:08.910 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: OK.

00:07:08.910 --> 00:07:10.660 align:middle line:84%
That's when we began
observing sleep.

00:07:10.660 --> 00:07:13.430 align:middle line:84%
And then over time sleep
labs started up and such.

00:07:13.430 --> 00:07:15.810 align:middle line:84%
Can you talk about
what that phenomena

00:07:15.810 --> 00:07:17.250 align:middle line:90%
brought to our awareness?

00:07:17.250 --> 00:07:17.750 align:middle line:90%
>>DUFF: Yes.

00:07:17.750 --> 00:07:21.590 align:middle line:84%
We're talking about in the
Western scientific tradition.

00:07:21.590 --> 00:07:26.450 align:middle line:84%
Until the development of our
brain imaging techniques,

00:07:26.450 --> 00:07:28.770 align:middle line:84%
scientists in the West
assumed that nothing happened

00:07:28.770 --> 00:07:33.315 align:middle line:84%
when we sleep, that our brains
were like the lamp next to us

00:07:33.315 --> 00:07:35.050 align:middle line:84%
that we turn off
when we go to sleep

00:07:35.050 --> 00:07:37.480 align:middle line:84%
and we turn it back
on when we wake up.

00:07:37.480 --> 00:07:41.400 align:middle line:84%
But then with the development
of the electroencephalogram

00:07:41.400 --> 00:07:44.350 align:middle line:84%
we began to be able
to record brain waves.

00:07:44.350 --> 00:07:47.500 align:middle line:84%
And what Aserinsky did, he
brought his eight-year-old son

00:07:47.500 --> 00:07:51.430 align:middle line:84%
into the sleep lab
and hooked him up

00:07:51.430 --> 00:07:53.470 align:middle line:84%
and was watching
his brain waves.

00:07:53.470 --> 00:07:57.110 align:middle line:84%
And his son fell asleep
and started dreaming,

00:07:57.110 --> 00:07:59.970 align:middle line:84%
and his eyes were flickering
around underneath their lids.

00:07:59.970 --> 00:08:03.790 align:middle line:84%
And that's when he realized--
The brain waves all

00:08:03.790 --> 00:08:05.520 align:middle line:90%
got really intense.

00:08:05.520 --> 00:08:07.630 align:middle line:84%
And that's when he
realized, that he

00:08:07.630 --> 00:08:10.560 align:middle line:84%
made the connection between
sleep and brain wave

00:08:10.560 --> 00:08:14.160 align:middle line:84%
activity and dreaming
and brain wave activity.

00:08:14.160 --> 00:08:16.520 align:middle line:84%
That put an end to the
notion that nothing

00:08:16.520 --> 00:08:18.800 align:middle line:90%
happens while we sleep.

00:08:18.800 --> 00:08:21.937 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Let's talk about
Threshold Consciousness.

00:08:21.937 --> 00:08:23.270 align:middle line:90%
You talk about that in the book.

00:08:23.270 --> 00:08:25.142 align:middle line:90%
What is Threshold Consciousness?

00:08:25.142 --> 00:08:26.850 align:middle line:84%
>>DUFF: Well, we like
to think that we're

00:08:26.850 --> 00:08:30.850 align:middle line:84%
either awake or asleep and
there's no realm in between.

00:08:30.850 --> 00:08:35.380 align:middle line:84%
But in fact what I've called
Threshold Consciousness

00:08:35.380 --> 00:08:37.059 align:middle line:90%
is a blending of the two.

00:08:37.059 --> 00:08:41.330 align:middle line:84%
And neurological research has
confirmed that our brains just

00:08:41.330 --> 00:08:43.929 align:middle line:84%
don't shut down all at
once like a light bulb.

00:08:43.929 --> 00:08:46.740 align:middle line:84%
Different parts of
our brain, once they

00:08:46.740 --> 00:08:48.230 align:middle line:84%
get tired-- for
example, if we've

00:08:48.230 --> 00:08:50.770 align:middle line:84%
been reading for a long time,
the parts of our brain we use

00:08:50.770 --> 00:08:53.840 align:middle line:84%
when we're reading--
will, in a sense,

00:08:53.840 --> 00:08:57.110 align:middle line:84%
kind of close down for the
day before other parts.

00:08:57.110 --> 00:09:01.240 align:middle line:84%
And so we have these mixed
states of part awake,

00:09:01.240 --> 00:09:06.590 align:middle line:84%
part asleep that manifests
in many different ways.

00:09:06.590 --> 00:09:09.170 align:middle line:90%
It can manifest as sleepwalking.

00:09:09.170 --> 00:09:10.715 align:middle line:84%
It can manifest as
sleep paralysis.

00:09:10.715 --> 00:09:14.610 align:middle line:84%
It can manifest
as creative ideas.

00:09:14.610 --> 00:09:18.130 align:middle line:84%
A lot of artists have mined
those threshold states

00:09:18.130 --> 00:09:19.517 align:middle line:90%
for inspiration.

00:09:19.517 --> 00:09:20.100 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yes.

00:09:20.100 --> 00:09:21.837 align:middle line:84%
In fact, in a moment
we'll take a look

00:09:21.837 --> 00:09:23.420 align:middle line:84%
at what that looks
like, sleepwalking.

00:09:23.420 --> 00:09:26.704 align:middle line:84%
It's a funny little video that
a man's family took of him,

00:09:26.704 --> 00:09:28.120 align:middle line:84%
and he's with his
little daughter.

00:09:28.120 --> 00:09:31.050 align:middle line:84%
But first, before we go
to that video in a sec,

00:09:31.050 --> 00:09:32.800 align:middle line:84%
I wanted to talk about
that a little more,

00:09:32.800 --> 00:09:37.060 align:middle line:84%
because that threshold area is
also where a lot of information

00:09:37.060 --> 00:09:40.060 align:middle line:84%
flows through for people
that tend to pay attention

00:09:40.060 --> 00:09:42.770 align:middle line:90%
to intuitive impulses and such.

00:09:42.770 --> 00:09:44.950 align:middle line:84%
And in your book,
you talked about how

00:09:44.950 --> 00:09:47.790 align:middle line:84%
Nabokov, the author of
"Lolita" and other books,

00:09:47.790 --> 00:09:50.370 align:middle line:84%
received a lot of
his information

00:09:50.370 --> 00:09:53.745 align:middle line:84%
as he was drifting in
that between space.

00:09:53.745 --> 00:09:56.120 align:middle line:84%
>>DUFF: Well, a lot of artists
have and a lot of writers,

00:09:56.120 --> 00:09:57.300 align:middle line:90%
absolutely.

00:09:57.300 --> 00:09:58.760 align:middle line:84%
I think it was
Steinbeck who coined

00:09:58.760 --> 00:10:00.180 align:middle line:90%
the phrase Committee of Sleep.

00:10:00.180 --> 00:10:00.380 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yes.

00:10:00.380 --> 00:10:02.060 align:middle line:84%
>>DUFF: I'll let my Committee
of Sleep work on this,

00:10:02.060 --> 00:10:04.130 align:middle line:84%
and I'll have an idea in
the morning of what to do.

00:10:04.130 --> 00:10:04.750 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yes.

00:10:04.750 --> 00:10:05.791 align:middle line:90%
>>DUFF: It's very common.

00:10:05.791 --> 00:10:09.640 align:middle line:84%
I like to take my problems, both
in writing as well as my life

00:10:09.640 --> 00:10:11.700 align:middle line:90%
problems, to my sleep.

00:10:11.700 --> 00:10:15.860 align:middle line:84%
And that's why I really
cherish those times

00:10:15.860 --> 00:10:19.520 align:middle line:84%
of falling asleep and
waking up, because that's

00:10:19.520 --> 00:10:25.480 align:middle line:84%
when we can kind of access
the larger realms of awareness

00:10:25.480 --> 00:10:28.645 align:middle line:84%
that we come to in sleep that
are hard to sometimes bring up

00:10:28.645 --> 00:10:29.697 align:middle line:90%
to conscious awareness.

00:10:29.697 --> 00:10:30.280 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yes.

00:10:30.280 --> 00:10:35.350 align:middle line:84%
And I notice in my own life I
have these very weird things

00:10:35.350 --> 00:10:38.220 align:middle line:84%
that happen if I'm particularly
tired, for example.

00:10:38.220 --> 00:10:39.920 align:middle line:84%
You know how you've
been going, going?

00:10:39.920 --> 00:10:41.150 align:middle line:90%
You're very tired.

00:10:41.150 --> 00:10:45.630 align:middle line:84%
In those states, when I start
drifting into the sleep process

00:10:45.630 --> 00:10:47.700 align:middle line:84%
but I'm not there yet,
I'm still conscious,

00:10:47.700 --> 00:10:50.830 align:middle line:90%
I see full-on animated cartoons.

00:10:50.830 --> 00:10:54.740 align:middle line:84%
And I watch bizarre cartoons
and think, what is up?

00:10:54.740 --> 00:10:58.830 align:middle line:84%
Or sometimes see
almost a negative world

00:10:58.830 --> 00:11:02.077 align:middle line:84%
of shadows of real
people, and I almost

00:11:02.077 --> 00:11:03.160 align:middle line:90%
feel like an eavesdropper.

00:11:03.160 --> 00:11:04.300 align:middle line:90%
I'm watching them.

00:11:04.300 --> 00:11:06.470 align:middle line:84%
I'm listening to
their conversations.

00:11:06.470 --> 00:11:09.345 align:middle line:84%
And it's usually
rather innocuous.

00:11:09.345 --> 00:11:13.460 align:middle line:84%
It's just kind of dropping
into someone else's reality.

00:11:13.460 --> 00:11:16.840 align:middle line:84%
I don't know what
dimension or whatnot,

00:11:16.840 --> 00:11:20.730 align:middle line:84%
but I've always found it so
amazing what the being will

00:11:20.730 --> 00:11:21.840 align:middle line:90%
choose to show to itself--

00:11:21.840 --> 00:11:22.690 align:middle line:90%
>>DUFF: Isn't it?

00:11:22.690 --> 00:11:23.190 align:middle line:90%
I know.

00:11:23.190 --> 00:11:24.969 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: --especially
with the cartoons.

00:11:24.969 --> 00:11:25.760 align:middle line:90%
>>DUFF: Absolutely.

00:11:25.760 --> 00:11:27.860 align:middle line:84%
Sometimes people see
geometric patterns--

00:11:27.860 --> 00:11:28.420 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yeah, that too.

00:11:28.420 --> 00:11:29.840 align:middle line:84%
>>DUFF: --or they
hear wild sounds

00:11:29.840 --> 00:11:34.440 align:middle line:84%
or have a sensation of swelling
up or being confined, going

00:11:34.440 --> 00:11:36.696 align:middle line:90%
down to the size of a pea.

00:11:36.696 --> 00:11:38.350 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Hearing
your name called out.

00:11:38.350 --> 00:11:39.010 align:middle line:90%
>>DUFF: Absolutely.

00:11:39.010 --> 00:11:40.660 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Voices calling
your name out, very common.

00:11:40.660 --> 00:11:41.493 align:middle line:90%
>>DUFF: Very common.

00:11:41.493 --> 00:11:44.050 align:middle line:84%
And you know, I've talked to,
over the years as a counselor,

00:11:44.050 --> 00:11:46.220 align:middle line:84%
many people who've
lost loved ones,

00:11:46.220 --> 00:11:50.220 align:middle line:84%
and they will
often report having

00:11:50.220 --> 00:11:53.310 align:middle line:84%
an encounter with that
child or that parent

00:11:53.310 --> 00:11:56.080 align:middle line:84%
or that friend who's died
as they're falling asleep

00:11:56.080 --> 00:11:58.840 align:middle line:84%
or waking up in those
in-between worlds.

00:11:58.840 --> 00:12:02.850 align:middle line:84%
So I think it's very common for
more to pass into our awareness

00:12:02.850 --> 00:12:05.034 align:middle line:84%
than does normally in
our conscious going

00:12:05.034 --> 00:12:05.825 align:middle line:90%
about our business.

00:12:05.825 --> 00:12:06.949 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Rigid conscious--

00:12:06.949 --> 00:12:07.870 align:middle line:90%
>>DUFF: Right.

00:12:07.870 --> 00:12:09.990 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: --left half
of the brain aspect.

00:12:09.990 --> 00:12:10.490 align:middle line:90%
>>DUFF: Yes.

00:12:10.490 --> 00:12:11.031 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: OK.

00:12:11.031 --> 00:12:14.556 align:middle line:84%
So while we're talking
about this crossover state

00:12:14.556 --> 00:12:15.930 align:middle line:84%
and you'd mentioned
sleepwalking,

00:12:15.930 --> 00:12:16.560 align:middle line:90%
that's a good time.

00:12:16.560 --> 00:12:18.450 align:middle line:84%
We were going to show it
later, but let's go ahead

00:12:18.450 --> 00:12:20.620 align:middle line:84%
and take a look at this
little video of this guy who

00:12:20.620 --> 00:12:23.210 align:middle line:84%
is being shown a video
of himself sleepwalking.

00:12:23.210 --> 00:12:24.330 align:middle line:90%
He looks like a zombie.

00:12:24.330 --> 00:12:24.820 align:middle line:90%
>>DUFF: Poor guy.

00:12:24.820 --> 00:12:25.800 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Just for fun.

00:12:25.800 --> 00:12:27.908 align:middle line:90%
OK.

